commentBody:
@Barry Ancona
So I'm not the only one who thought of Andrezj right away!

I think he said recently he's swearing off late-week puzzles, but I hope he sees it.

@Barry Ancona and @Linda Jo
  yes I thought of Andrzej for 31A too. I'm going to post tomorrow to suggest he do it from the archive because so many inquiring minds will want to know what HE thought of 31A.
 So is this one trivia-free enough that he won't hate the suggestion? Maybe I'd better check.

@HeathieJ

Thanks for reading my review.

I'm glad relinking your NYT data to xwordstats worked.

@L.A. Bruce D

Thanks. I figured it out retrospectively, once I'd entered the P and got the gold star. 
Neither "kindergarten" nor the "K" abbreviation are used in the UK. But I've seen enough references to US grade spans like "K-5" to be able to see "pre-K" in PREK, given the context of the clue.

@Oikofuge

Odie is from the comic strip "Garfield". 

Sara Lee is a company famous for its desserts - now defunct in most regions of the world. In the UK, they were most famous for their Double Chocolate Gateaux.

@Oikofuge

Off topic,  but I really loved the SCE to AUX shirt you mentioned yesterday.  

What an inspiring moment!  It shows how paying attention to oddities can sometimes save you.

@Joan

I, too, was one letter off, and as always it drove me crazy:  TWEeK vs. TWEAK, crossing MESe vs MESA, which I should have seen.

For me, it's often the vowels.  Although yesterday it was a Y.

@CaptainQuahog 
Early on, my girlfriend would pull out a Maleska puzzle so we could do it together.  Then as our relationship progressed she would say, "Let's try getting together on Friday or maybe Saturday".  It took me a while to realize the relationship got better because we ere doing harder puzzles together...  
Now my wife and I have spent decades working through the "Maleska and Shortz eras".  There has always been a progression from easy to harder over the week, but maybe not always rigidly enforced.  YMMV

@HeathieJ

That was my confusion; I was beginning to wonder if FAD was an abbreviation I wasn't aware of.

(The clue works well without "briefly"; for me it was a very confusing misdirect!)

@HeathieJ

Yeah, I've thought that some way to tell the puzzle you're done other than have it all filled in would be nice.

On the other hand, given the mess they've made of the forum, God knows what would happen if they tried to do that.

@Sean

Assuming the San Jose location is in California, you're correct - Sunday and Monday puzzles are available to you at 3 PM the day before.  All the other days come to you at 7 PM, you lucky duck (in a row?)

And don't give up - find  a foothold or two and see where they lead.  You may surprise yourself!  (And you will find some expert advice here from everyone's favorite XWD maven, Deb Amlen: <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/article/how-to-solve-a-crossword-puzzle.html" target="_blank">https://www.nytimes.com/article/how-to-solve-a-crossword-puzzle.html</a> )

@DJ

Actually, I could see a 3-tiered streak: blue, gold, and platinum.

Blue doesn't care when you finish them. Might require a few more lines of code because a streak could get filled in retroactively. But hey, that would pull a lot of us back into the archives more often.

@Ellie R.

A clever clue, for sure, but not original. This is the 12th time it has appeared, clued to ASSET twice (a question mark was included those two times) and ESTATE the other 10 times (no ?). 

